arianism debate. To conclude, he introduces a concept of ‘critical community’ – a dialogical, self-reflective community critical of its own tradition – to show that collective identities can be constructed in critical dialogue with the tradition and values of community.Find Out MoreRead the Introduction online for free (pdf)"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDemocracy. 4aPolitics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107804510 cprintz978074864405640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748644063?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748644063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748644063/original  a978-3-11-078045-1  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK